"PGauxiliaryFunctions.pl"
);

TEXT(beginproblem());

$showPartialCorrectAnswers = 1;

$a = random(-2,-1,1);
$c = random(2,5,1); # where the function t^2(t - c) crosses the x-axis
$b = $c + random(1,2,1);

BEGIN_TEXT

The velocity function (in meters per second) for a particle moving along a line is given by \( v(t) = t^3 - $c t^2  \).  
Find the displacement of the particle during the time interval between $a and $b seconds.  
$BR$BR
Displacement = \{ans_rule(30) \} (Include the correct \{ helpLink('units') \}.) 


$BR$BR
To calculate the distance traveled by the particle during the time interval between $a and $b seconds, we must split the integral of the absolute value of velocity into a sum of two integrals   
$BR$BR
Distance = \( \displaystyle \int_{$a}^{$b} | t^3 - $c t^2 | \, dt = \int_{$a}^{k} v_1(t) \,  dt + \int_{k}^{$b} v_2(t) \, dt \)
$BR$BR
where \( v_1(t) \) and \( v_2(t) \) are functions and \( k \) is a constant such that
$BR$BR
\( v_1(t) = \) \{ ans_rule(30) \}
$BR
\( v_2(t) = \) \{ ans_rule(30) \}
$BR
\( k = \) \{ ans_rule(30) \}
$BR 
Distance = \{ans_rule(30) \} (Include the correct \{ helpLink('units') \}.)
$BR$BR

(Hint: Draw a graph of the velocity function.)

END_TEXT

$displacement = ($b**4 - $a**4) / 4 + $c * ($a**3 - $b**3) / 3; 
$distance = $c**4 / 6 + ($a**4 + $b**4) / 4 - $c * ($a**3 + $b**3) / 3;
$v1 = "- (t**3 - $c * t**2)";
$v2 = "t**3 - $c * t**2";

ANS(num_cmp($displacement, units=>'m'));
ANS(fun_cmp($v1,vars=>'t',limits=>[-7,-6]));
ANS(fun_cmp($v2,vars=>'t',limits=>[6,7]));
ANS(num_cmp($c));
ANS(num_cmp($distance, units=>'m'));

ENDDOCUMENT();
